ge and Dr. Johnson''.  The book consists of quotations from Johnson's ''[[A Dictionary of the English Language|Dictionary]]'', accompanied by Skargon's wood engravings of the two cats, contextually associated with the dictionary entries.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Lily & Hodge & Dr Johnson |last=Skargon |first=Yvonne |authorlink=Yvonne Skargon |year=1999 |publisher=Primose Hill Press |location=Newville, Pennsylvania |isbn=978-1901648171 |oclc=898329986}}</ref> Hodge also appears in Charlie Fletcher's \"Silvertongue\" as a brave and fearless cat.  Hodge also appears in [[Samuel Beckett]]'s early dramatic fragment ''[[Human Wishes]]''.  In [[M. C. Beaton]]'s ''[[Agatha Raisin]]'' novel series, the heroine's cats are named Hodge and Boswell. The English critic, essayist and poet [[Leigh Hunt]] wrote an essay entitled \"The Cat by the Fire\" which features an imaginary description of how some of Samuel Johnson's friends and acquaintances would have related to Hodge the cat.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hunt |first=Leigh |author-link=Leigh Hunt |url=http://essays.quotidiana.org/hunt/cat_by_the_fire/ |year=1834 |editor-last=Madden |editor-first=Patrick  |publication-date=30 December 2007 |website=Quotidiana |title=The Cat by the Fire |access-date=27 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in the City of London]]\n*[[List of cats]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Tambling |first=Kirsten |title=Hodge's History of Cats |year=2014 |publisher=Tyburn Tree |location=Cirencester |isbn=978-0-9926224-1-1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thegreatcat.org/cats-enlightenment-part-3-samuel-johnson-hodge/ Samuel Johnson and his Cat Hodge]\n*[http://www.moggies.co.uk/stories/finecat.html Popular account] of Hodge's life\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050208054430/http://www.stanford.edu/~evans/LitLondon/Johnson.htm Pictorial account] of Hodge's legacy\n*[[Project Gutenberg]] abridged e-text of Boswell's ''[http://onlinebooks.libra