{"title_page": "Allan Jacobs", "text_new": "{{for|persons of a similar name|Alan Jacobs (disambiguation)}}\n'''Allan B. Jacobs''' (born 29 December 1928) is an urban designer, renowned for his publications and research on [[urban design]].  His well-known paper ''\"Toward an Urban Design Manifesto\"'', written with  [[Donald Appleyard]], describes how cities should be laid out.\n\nPrior to teaching at Berkeley, Professor Jacobs taught at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and worked on planning projects in the City of [[Pittsburgh]] and for the [[Ford Foundation]] in Calcutta, India, and spent eight years as Director of the [[San Francisco]] Department of City Planning. In 1978 Jacobs presented his \u2018Making City Planning Work\u2019 that offered reflections on his experiences as the San Francisco planning director from 1967-75 and guided on bureaucratic and political processes navigation that often hamper the realization of desired planning policies and outcomes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of the City|last=Caves|first=R. W.|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|isbn=9780415252256|location=|pages=403}}</ref> Honors include a Guggenheim Fellowship, the Berkeley Citation, and the Kevin Lynch Award from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.\n\nJacobs taught in the Department of City and Regional Planning at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] from 1975 until 2001, teaching courses in city planning and urban design and serving twice as the department's chair.  He is currently a [[Professor Emeritus|Professor emeritus]].  He is currently a consultant in city planning and urban design with projects in California, Oregon, and Brazil, among others.\n\n==Education ==\nJacobs earned a [[Bachelor of Architecture]], [[cum laude]], from [[Miami University]] and a [[master's degree]] in city planning from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1954.  He then attended the [[Harvard Graduate School of Design]].\n\nFrom 1954 to 1955, Jacobs was studying city planning as a [[Fulbright Scholar]] at [[University College London]].\n\n==Notable works==\n* The [[Urban Design]] Element of the [[San Francisco]] [[General Plan]]\n* Allan Jacobs and [[Donald Appleyard]], ''Toward an Urban Design Manifesto''.  Working Paper published 1982; republished with a prologue in the [[Journal of the American Planning Association]], 1987.<ref>[https://moodle.unitec.ac.nz/pluginfile.php/431150/mod_resource/content/1/urban-design-manifesto-by-jacobs-1987.pdf Allan Jacobs and Donald Appleyard, ''Toward an Urban Design Manifesto'', APA Journal, Winter 1987]</ref>\n* ''Making City Planning Work'' (1980)\n* ''Looking at Cities'' (1985)\n* ''Great Streets'' (1995)\n* ''The Boulevard Book'' (2003) with Elizabeth MacDonald and Yodan Rofe\n* ''The Good City: Reflections and Imaginations'' (2011)\n\n==Honors==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060202010051/http://www.acsp.org/news/MayJune99/lynch_award.html Kevin Lynch Award], presented at MIT's \"Imaging the City\" symposium, 1999. \n* [[American Institute of Architects|AIA]] Excellence in Education Award, California Chapter, 1994\n* Resident in Architecture, [[American Academy in Rome]], 1996<ref>[http://www.aarome.org/fellows-affiliated-fellows-residents-1990-2010 American Academy in Rome,  Fellows - Affiliated Fellows - Residents 1990-2010]</ref>\n* [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] [[List of Guggenheim Fellowships awarded in 1981|awarded in 1981]]<ref>[http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/allan-b-jacobs/ John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation Fellows, Category: Humanities, Field of Study: Architecture, Planning and Design, Competition: US & Canada]</ref>\n* [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholar]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060724062112/http://www.pps.org/info/placemakingtools/placemakers/ajacobs Allan B. Jacobs], Project for Public Spaces. \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060301215224/http://www.brunerfoundation.org/rba/p/jac.html Allan B. Jacobs bio], Bruner Foundation. \n*[http://www.calgary.ca/portal/server.pt/gateway/PTARGS_0_2_777_203_0_43/http%3B/content.calgary.ca/CCA/City+Hall/News/Awards/Awards+Given/Mayors+Urban+Design+Awards/Jurors/Allan+Jacobs.htm Allan Jacobs bio]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, City of Calgary (Alberta, Canada).\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100620125149/http://www.ced.berkeley.edu/ced/people/query.php?id=158&dept=all&title=all&first=Allan&last=Jacobs&ced&berkeley Allan Jacobs], University of California, Berkeley.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060207101147/http://arch.ced.berkeley.edu/people/faculty/index.htm College of Environmental Design], University of California, Berkeley.\n*Barry, Sean. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070313083028/http://www.dailycal.org/sharticle.php?id=20792 \"Speakers Envision Downtown's Future\"], ''The Daily Californian'', January 19, 2006.\n*Pollack, Theo Mackey. [http://www.theamericanconservative.com/urbs/what-makes-a-great-street/ \"What Makes a Great Street?\"], New Urbs,''The American Conservative'', April 13, 2018. \n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobs, Allan}}\n[[Category:Urban theorists]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Urban designers]]\n[[Category:American urban planners]]\n[[Category:American sociologists]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|persons of a similar name|Alan Jacobs (disambiguation)}}\n'''Allan B. Jacobs''' (born 29 December 1928) is an urban designer, renowned for his publications and research on [[urban design]].  His well-known paper ''\"Toward an Urban Design Manifesto\"'', written with  [[Donald Appleyard]], describes how cities should be laid out.\n\nPrior to teaching at Berkeley, Professor Jacobs taught at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and worked on planning projects in the City of [[Pittsburgh]] and for the [[Ford Foundation]] in Calcutta, India, and spent eight years as Director of the [[San Francisco]] Department of City Planning. In 1978 Jacobs presented his \u2018Making City Planning Work\u2019 that offered reflections on his experiences as the San Francisco planning director from 1967-75 and guided on bureaucratic and political processes navigation that often hamper the realization of desired planing policies and outcomes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of the City|last=Caves|first=R. W.|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|isbn=9780415252256|location=|pages=403}}</ref> Honors include a Guggenheim Fellowship, the Berkeley Citation, and the Kevin Lynch Award from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.\n\nJacobs taught in the Department of City and Regional Planning at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] from 1975 until 2001, teaching courses in city planning and urban design and serving twice as the department's chair.  He is currently a [[Professor Emeritus|Professor emeritus]].  He is currently a consultant in city planning and urban design with projects in California, Oregon, and Brazil, among others.\n\n==Education ==\nJacobs earned a [[Bachelor of Architecture]], [[cum laude]], from [[Miami University]] and a [[master's degree]] in city planning from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1954.  He then attended the [[Harvard Graduate School of Design]].\n\nFrom 1954 to 1955, Jacobs was studying city planning as a [[Fulbright Scholar]] at [[University College London]].\n\n==Notable works==\n* The [[Urban Design]] Element of the [[San Francisco]] [[General Plan]]\n* Allan Jacobs and [[Donald Appleyard]], ''Toward an Urban Design Manifesto''.  Working Paper published 1982; republished with a prologue in the [[Journal of the American Planning Association]], 1987.<ref>[https://moodle.unitec.ac.nz/pluginfile.php/431150/mod_resource/content/1/urban-design-manifesto-by-jacobs-1987.pdf Allan Jacobs and Donald Appleyard, ''Toward an Urban Design Manifesto'', APA Journal, Winter 1987]</ref>\n* ''Making City Planning Work'' (1980)\n* ''Looking at Cities'' (1985)\n* ''Great Streets'' (1995)\n* ''The Boulevard Book'' (2003) with Elizabeth MacDonald and Yodan Rofe\n* ''The Good City: Reflections and Imaginations'' (2011)\n\n==Honors==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060202010051/http://www.acsp.org/news/MayJune99/lynch_award.html Kevin Lynch Award], presented at MIT's \"Imaging the City\" symposium, 1999. \n* [[American Institute of Architects|AIA]] Excellence in Education Award, California Chapter, 1994\n* Resident in Architecture, [[American Academy in Rome]], 1996<ref>[http://www.aarome.org/fellows-affiliated-fellows-residents-1990-2010 American Academy in Rome,  Fellows - Affiliated Fellows - Residents 1990-2010]</ref>\n* [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] [[List of Guggenheim Fellowships awarded in 1981|awarded in 1981]]<ref>[http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/allan-b-jacobs/ John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation Fellows, Category: Humanities, Field of Study: Architecture, Planning and Design, Competition: US & Canada]</ref>\n* [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholar]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060724062112/http://www.pps.org/info/placemakingtools/placemakers/ajacobs Allan B. Jacobs], Project for Public Spaces. \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060301215224/http://www.brunerfoundation.org/rba/p/jac.html Allan B. Jacobs bio], Bruner Foundation. \n*[http://www.calgary.ca/portal/server.pt/gateway/PTARGS_0_2_777_203_0_43/http%3B/content.calgary.ca/CCA/City+Hall/News/Awards/Awards+Given/Mayors+Urban+Design+Awards/Jurors/Allan+Jacobs.htm Allan Jacobs bio]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, City of Calgary (Alberta, Canada).\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100620125149/http://www.ced.berkeley.edu/ced/people/query.php?id=158&dept=all&title=all&first=Allan&last=Jacobs&ced&berkeley Allan Jacobs], University of California, Berkeley.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060207101147/http://arch.ced.berkeley.edu/people/faculty/index.htm College of Environmental Design], University of California, Berkeley.\n*Barry, Sean. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070313083028/http://www.dailycal.org/sharticle.php?id=20792 \"Speakers Envision Downtown's Future\"], ''The Daily Californian'', January 19, 2006.\n*Pollack, Theo Mackey. [http://www.theamericanconservative.com/urbs/what-makes-a-great-street/ \"What Makes a Great Street?\"], New Urbs,''The American Conservative'', April 13, 2018. \n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobs, Allan}}\n[[Category:Urban theorists]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Urban designers]]\n[[Category:American urban planners]]\n[[Category:American sociologists]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Jacobs"}
{"title_page": "Flintshire Historical Society journal", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=February 2013}}\n{{Italic title}}\nThe '''''Flintshire Historical Society Journal''''' is an annual [[magazine]] in [[English language|English]], containing transcripts and articles relating to the county, with book reviews and society notes. It is published by the Flintshire Historical Society, a registered charity founded in 1911 to collect and publish [[archaeology|archaeological]] and [[history|historical]] material about [[Flintshire]]. From 1911 to 1976, the magazine was published as the ''Flintshire Historical Society Publications''. In 1978 it obtained its current name.\n\nThe magazine has been digitized by the [[National Library of Wales#Welsh Journals Online|Welsh Journals Online]] project at the [[National Library of Wales]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://welshjournals.llgc.org.uk/browse/listissues/llgc-id:1256711 ''Flintshire Historical Society publications''] at [[Welsh Journals Online]]\n*[http://welshjournals.llgc.org.uk/browse/listissues/llgc-id:1218518 ''Flintshire Historical Society Journal''] at Welsh Journals Online\n*[http://www.flintshirehistoricalsociety.org.uk/ Flintshire Historical Society website]\n\n[[Category:English-language magazines]]\n[[Category:British annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1911]]\n[[Category:British history magazines]]\n[[Category:Local interest magazines]]\n\n\n{{hist-mag-stub}}\n{{Wales-stub}}\n{{UK-mag-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=February 2013}}\n{{Italic title}}\nThe '''''Flintshire Historical Society Journal''''' is an annual [[magazine]] in [[English language|English]], containing transcripts and articles relating to the county, with book reviews and society notes. It is published by the Flintshire Historical Society, a registered charity founded in 1911 to collect and publish [[archaeology|archaeological]] and [[history|historical]] material about [[Flintshire]]. From 1911 to 1976, the magazine was published as the ''Flintshire Historical Society Publications''. In 1978 it obtained its current name.\n\nThe magazine has been digitized by the [[National Library of Wales#Welsh Journals Online|Welsh Journals Online]] project at the [[National Library of Wales]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://welshjournals.llgc.org.uk/browse/listissues/llgc-id:1256711 ''Flintshire Historical Society publications''] at [[Welsh Journals Online]]\n*[http://welshjournals.llgc.org.uk/browse/listissues/llgc-id:1218518 ''Flintshire Historical Society Journal''] at Welsh Journals Online\n*[http://www.flintshirehistoricalsociety.org.uk/ Flintshire Historical Society website]\n\n[[Category:English-language magazines]]\n[[Category:Annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1911]]\n[[Category:British history magazines]]\n[[Category:Local interest magazines]]\n\n{{hist-mag-stub}}\n{{Wales-stub}}\n{{UK-mag-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flintshire_Historical_Society_journal"}
{"title_page": "Reginald James", "text_new": "{{for|the British explorer|Reginald W. James}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n'''Reginald Alfred John James''' (1 June 1893 \u2013 27 September 1944) was an [[Australia]]n politician. He was a [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|Country Party]] member of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] from 1943 to 1944, representing the electorate of [[electoral district of Bulla and Dalhousie|Bulla and Dalhousie]].\n\nJames was born in America, and lived his early years in [[Swan Hill, Victoria|Swan Hill]]. He served in [[World War I]] in [[France]] with the 29th battalion, and returned after the war to his family's dairy farming and grazing property at [[Garfield, Victoria|Garfield]].<ref name=\"mladies\">{{cite news |title=MLA Dies Suddenly At House |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11363037|newspaper=The Argus |location=Melbourne |date=28 September 1944 |page=3 |accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref> He also later owned a chain of milk bars in [[Melbourne]]. James was well known in the dairy industry around Australia, and served as secretary and official advocate of the Milk Producers' Association from its inception until his death. He also served as editor of the Milk Producer publication, founder and honorary secretary of the Metropolitan Milk Council Free Milk Scheme, secretary of the Milk Standard Institute, president of the Gippsland United Progress Associations, and as a member of the council of the Victorian Chamber of Agriculture.<ref name=\"mladies\" /><ref name=\"parl\">{{cite web\n | title = Re-Member: James, Reginald Alfred John\n | publisher = [[Parliament of Victoria]]\n | url = http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=1179\n | accessdate = 2012-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\"rajames\">{{cite news |title=R. A. James |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59655015|newspaper=Kilmore Free Press |location=Kilmore |date=20 May 1943 |page=2 |accessdate=2012-11-28}}</ref>\n\nJames first attempted to enter politics at a [[1929 Gippsland West state by-election|1929 by-election]], when he contested the seat of [[electoral district of Gippsland West|Gippsland West]] as a [[Nationalist Party of Australia|Nationalist]] candidate. He ran what was widely touted as a strong campaign, but lost to Country Party candidate [[Matthew Bennett (politician)|Matthew Bennett]].<ref name=\"1929race\">{{cite news |title=Gippsland West - By-Election Tomorrow |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4044398|newspaper=The Argus |location=Melbourne |date=18 October 1929 |page=8 |accessdate=2012-11-23}}</ref> He again contested the seat at the [[1929 Victorian state election|1929 state election]], but lost to Bennett once more.<ref name=\"parl\" />\n\nJames won election on his third attempt at the [[1943 Victorian state election|1943 state election]], when as a Country Party candidate, he won the [[United Australia Party]] seat of [[electoral district of Bulla and Dalhousie|Bulla and Dalhousie]] by a margin of 933 votes.<ref name=\"votes\">{{cite news |title=Final Stage of Election Results - Bulla-Dalhousie Won By C.P.|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11348125|newspaper=The Argus |location=Melbourne |date=22 June 1943 |page=4 |accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref> His political career was to be short-lived, however, as he died suddenly in office on 27 September 1944. James had finished speaking to an electoral redistribution bill in parliament, left the chamber, and collapsed and died in the lobby of Parliament House before medical assistance could be rendered.<ref name=\"mladies\" /><ref name=\"topic\">{{cite news |title=Member's Collapse in Victorian Parliament|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42433403|newspaper=Cairns Post |location=Cairns |date=29 September 1944 |page=5 |accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref> He was cremated at [[Springvale Crematorium]]. He was succeeded at the subsequent by-election by Country Party [[Leslie Webster (Australian politician)|Leslie Webster]], who had served with James on the executive of the Milk Producers' Association.<ref name=\"webster\">{{cite web\n | title = Re-Member: Webster, Leslie Leeder\n | publisher = [[Parliament of Victoria]]\n | url = http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=1523\n | accessdate = 2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\nHe was married with three children, one of whom was killed in a [[Royal Australian Air Force]] training accident in November 1942.<ref name=\"mladies\" />\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59655207 Maiden speech]\n* [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59655016 James' campaign advertisement from 1943 election]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Electoral district of Bulla and Dalhousie|Bulla and Dalhousie]] | before=[[Harry White (Australian politician)|Harry White]] | after=[[Leslie Webster (Australian politician)|Leslie Webster]] | years=1943&ndash;1944}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:James, Reginald Alfred John}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:National Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the British explorer|Reginald W. James}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n'''Reginald Alfred John James''' (1 June 1893 \u2013 27 September 1944) was an [[Australia]]n politician. He was a [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Victoria|Country Party]] member of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] from 1943 to 1944, representing the electorate of [[electoral district of Bulla and Dalhousie|Bulla and Dalhousie]].\n\nJames was born in America , and lived his early years in [[Swan Hill, Victoria|Swan Hill]]. He served in [[World War I]] in [[France]] with the 29th battalion, and returned after the war to his family's dairy farming and grazing property at [[Garfield, Victoria|Garfield]].<ref name=\"mladies\">{{cite news |title=MLA Dies Suddenly At House |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11363037|newspaper=The Argus |location=Melbourne |date=28 September 1944 |page=3 |accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref> He also later owned a chain of milk bars in [[Melbourne]]. James was well known in the dairy industry around Australia, and served as secretary and official advocate of the Milk Producers' Association from its inception until his death. He also served as editor of the Milk Producer publication, founder and honorary secretary of the Metropolitan Milk Council Free Milk Scheme, secretary of the Milk Standard Institute, president of the Gippsland United Progress Associations, and as a member of the council of the Victorian Chamber of Agriculture.<ref name=\"mladies\" /><ref name=\"parl\">{{cite web\n | title = Re-Member: James, Reginald Alfred John\n | publisher = [[Parliament of Victoria]]\n | url = http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=1179\n | accessdate = 2012-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\"rajames\">{{cite news |title=R. A. James |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59655015|newspaper=Kilmore Free Press |location=Kilmore |date=20 May 1943 |page=2 |accessdate=2012-11-28}}</ref>\n\nJames first attempted to enter politics at a [[1929 Gippsland West state by-election|1929 by-election]], when he contested the seat of [[electoral district of Gippsland West|Gippsland West]] as a [[Nationalist Party of Australia|Nationalist]] candidate. He ran what was widely touted as a strong campaign, but lost to Country Party candidate [[Matthew Bennett (politician)|Matthew Bennett]].<ref name=\"1929race\">{{cite news |title=Gippsland West - By-Election Tomorrow |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4044398|newspaper=The Argus |location=Melbourne |date=18 October 1929 |page=8 |accessdate=2012-11-23}}</ref> He again contested the seat at the [[1929 Victorian state election|1929 state election]], but lost to Bennett once more.<ref name=\"parl\" />\n\nJames won election on his third attempt at the [[1943 Victorian state election|1943 state election]], when as a Country Party candidate, he won the [[United Australia Party]] seat of [[electoral district of Bulla and Dalhousie|Bulla and Dalhousie]] by a margin of 933 votes.<ref name=\"votes\">{{cite news |title=Final Stage of Election Results - Bulla-Dalhousie Won By C.P.|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11348125|newspaper=The Argus |location=Melbourne |date=22 June 1943 |page=4 |accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref> His political career was to be short-lived, however, as he died suddenly in office on 27 September 1944. James had finished speaking to an electoral redistribution bill in parliament, left the chamber, and collapsed and died in the lobby of Parliament House before medical assistance could be rendered.<ref name=\"mladies\" /><ref name=\"topic\">{{cite news |title=Member's Collapse in Victorian Parliament|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42433403|newspaper=Cairns Post |location=Cairns |date=29 September 1944 |page=5 |accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref> He was cremated at [[Springvale Crematorium]]. He was succeeded at the subsequent by-election by Country Party [[Leslie Webster (Australian politician)|Leslie Webster]], who had served with James on the executive of the Milk Producers' Association.<ref name=\"webster\">{{cite web\n | title = Re-Member: Webster, Leslie Leeder\n | publisher = [[Parliament of Victoria]]\n | url = http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=1523\n | accessdate = 2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\nHe was married with three children, one of whom was killed in a [[Royal Australian Air Force]] training accident in November 1942.<ref name=\"mladies\" />\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59655207 Maiden speech]\n* [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59655016 James' campaign advertisement from 1943 election]\n